  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Motion Library Imports**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a handle on the Framer Motion library and its standard import procedure. The React and React-DOM versions are also noted. Now, I\'m shifting focus toward pinpointing the key features to prioritize in my build strategy.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Feature Focus**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the core features for this ecclesiastical conference app. Full-fidelity navigation is essential, so I\'m thinking a bottom navigation bar for Home, Schedule, Songs, and Map. A top drawer sidebar will house Registration, Speaker Bios, Ministry Meetings, and Youth Connect. I\'m especially excited about the Registration flow, complete with mock registration and a generated ticket! I\'m planning beautiful Speaker Bios cards and an engaging Youth Connect \"Message Board\".\n\n\n**Envisioning App Cohesion**\n\nI\'m striving to create a fully cohesive and lively app experience. I am designing a dynamic countdown to the conference start. The schedule will be searchable, filterable by day, with interactive details and note-taking features. I\'m also planning a rich song library with search, translation options, and theological notes.\n\n\n**Planning Feature Styling**\n\nI am now focusing on the app\'s visual presentation and how to incorporate it, and how to utilize Tailwind CSS to achieve this. Font size adjustments will be especially crucial to accommodate all attendees, so I am going to make that part of the plan. I will be sure to incorporate campus navigation, local directory, and travel planning, along with directions to get there!\n\n\n**Analyzing Font and Style Imports**\n\nNow I\'m diving into the `index.css` file. I found the Google Fonts import for \"Noto Serif\" and \"Work Sans\", which is exactly what the design requires, and I have found the corresponding CSS variables! This will make it simple to implement the design tokens.\n\n\n**Confirming CSS Configuration**\n\nI can confirm that the latest Tailwind CSS version (v4) is now successfully installed via `@tailwindcss/vite`, and I\'ve verified the `@import \"tailwindcss\";` directive in `src/index.css`. I\'m especially thrilled about the `@theme` configuration, which elegantly defines our design tokens using CSS variables, just as I imagined! This setup will make applying the design system a seamless experience.\n\nI\'m now implementing the code to split the code into manageable chunks. I will be sure to add `src/types.ts` to define types, and `src/data.ts` to define hardcoded data.\n\n\n**Structuring App Components**\n\nI\'m now deep in code design. I\'m focusing on creating modular components to keep `App.tsx` lightweight. I am creating `src/types.ts` to define types, and `src/data.ts` to define the hardcoded data. I\'m building out core components, starting with navigation elements like TopAppBar, BottomNavBar, and NavigationDrawer within `src/components/Navigation.tsx`. The home view will include countdowns, bento cards, speakers, and scripture in `src/components/HomeView.tsx`. The schedule, song library, interactive map, registration and speaker details are also designed. I am paying special attention to how YouthConnect will interact with the data.\n\n\n**Designing Interactive Components**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a scrollable message board for YouthConnect, envisioning custom colorful cards for prayers and quotes, complete with emoji integration. I am implementing this without external map API keys for robustness. I\'m prioritizing SVG/HTML-based interactive maps, campus visualizations, and a directions directory for an engaging user experience, prioritizing custom React styling.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 11
      nanos: 165033442
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
